title: For Sale:  FS: Canik TP9SA
postcontent: For sale: 1 used TP9SA by Canik.  Read the reviews on the WWW, check out the torture tests for this gun.  The trigger on this weapon is nice, comparable to some trigger upgrades for other vendors.  I have found it to be accurate (which is why I bought another), and my friends at the Remington plant here in HSV tell me they have a TP9SA to use as a "mule", and it's pushing 20,000 rounds and only beginning to show some wear on the guide rod.  I am told the mule has had zero issues as far as actually firing... in other words, these guns are well built.The "SA" is the TP9 with the decocker--I know it's a bit controversial, but the controversy is over-stated:  I have never, ever accidentally pressed the decocker.  I have tried to decock it while it was holstered (unloaded) and could not decock it "accidentally on purpose".Email via Armslist is the easiest way to reach me.Potential buyers will have a valid Alabama CCW (meaning you are also a valid AL resident), and willing to sign a Bill of Sale.  Face to face in the Huntsville area, public place (Cabelas, Wal-Mart, police stations).  $275 OBO, cold, hard cash only.

title: For Sale:  Krag 1984 Rifle
postcontent: DescriptionDealer Sold From the Estate of Vernon Cochran.Serial #15946I am no expert on firearms from this period but have consulted with collectors with more expertise in the field prior to posting. Please make sure to ask any questions on condition or request photos of specific areas of the gun prior to bidding if you have any concerns. I have tried to include information as accurate as possible in this listing but please verify if anything seems out of order or needs clarification.Firearm is in excellent condition from consults - considered to be greater than 85% valuation for KBB standards with conservative estimate. The Krag–Jørgensen is a repeating bolt action rifledesigned by the Norwegians Ole Herman Johannes Krag and Erik Jørgensen in the late 19th century. It was adopted as a standard arm by Denmark, the United States of America and Norway. About 300 were delivered to Boer forces of the South African Republic.A distinctive feature of the Krag–Jørgensen action was its magazine. While many other rifles of its era used an integral box magazine loaded by a charger or stripper clip, the magazine of the Krag–Jørgensen was integral with the receiver (the part of the rifle that houses the operating parts), featuring an opening on the right hand side with a hinged cover. Instead of a charger, single cartridges were inserted through the side opening, and were pushed up, around, and into the action by a spring follower.The design presented both advantages and disadvantages compared with a top-loading "box" magazine. A similar claw type clip would be made for the Krag that allowed the magazine to be loaded all at once, also known as the Krag "speedloader magazine". Normal loading was one cartridge at a time, and this could be done more easily with a Krag than a rifle with a "box" magazine. In fact, several cartridges can be dumped into the opened magazine of a Krag at once with no need for careful placement, and when shutting the magazine-door the cartridges are forced to line up correctly inside the magazine. The design was also easy to "top off", and unlike most top-loading magazines, the Krag–Jørgensen's magazine could be topped up without opening the rifle's bolt. The Krag–Jørgensen is a popular rifle among collectors, and is valued by shooters for its smooth action.Please ask any questions prior to bidding.Firearm is sold as is with no warranty.Please note WV residents must pay 6% sales tax. This item is available for purchase from my business as well and will be taken down if the reserve price has not been met and a customer desires to purchase it. title: For Sale:  Winchester M1 Garand Rifle, Very Rare Barrel
postcontent: I have found that according to Duffs research this rifle is probably Fall of 1943 production give or take a month or two in either direction and has many original Winchester parts from that time period with the usual overlap of parts types or variants..The barrel was made by Springfield but has a Winchester proof visible when the op rod is locked back. There are no Springfield proof marks meaning that Springfield never assembled it and only the drawing number, date and steel batch code are SA. This surprised us and after a few phone calls to elderly collectors and authorities on the Garand we were assured that although unusual and very rare this is a product of sharing or loaning of parts to keep production output unbroken by delays. Parts sharing or use of other manufacturers parts was more common place than most people think but was very poorly documented and it is likely that only a few hundred at the most may have been built this way and even fewer would have survived post war rebuildsThe bore has strong lands and grooves and has been through the rebuild process as there is hard chrome around the gas port .The Gas Plug is a single slot type which is period correct and is most likely a replacement as the blued finish is almost 100%.The Gas Lock is a Winchester and is surely original to the rifle as it is the beveled type and the finish wear matches the gas cylinder.The Gas Cylinder is a genuine Winchester round band, narrow base with the FSMWO diagonal saw cut.
